          <avActivityHighlights>Increase in danger of dry avalanches as a consequence of new snow and wind.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>As a consequence of sharply falling temperatures, snowfall and the occasionally storm force northwesterly wind, a treacherous avalanche situation will develop. &lt;br/&gt; Wednesday: The prevalence of avalanche prone locations and likelihood of triggering will increase during the course of the night. &lt;br/&gt; These conditions will bring about a rise in the danger of dry avalanches. Also at a distance from ridgelines occasionally large dry slab avalanches are possible. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Along the border with France and along the border with Switzerland the avalanche prone locations are more prevalent. Especially wind-loaded slopes: The fresh snow as well as all the wind slabs can be released by a single winter sport participant. Backcountry touring calls for caution and restraint.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>20 to 30 cm of snow, and up to 50 cm in some localities, will fall until the evening in all altitude zones. Especially in the northern areas bordering France and Switzerland. &lt;br/&gt; Towards its surface, the snowpack is soft and has a loosely bonded surface. &lt;br/&gt; The wind will transport the snow. The fresh wind slabs are bonding poorly with the old snowpack. &lt;br/&gt; Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes. &lt;br/&gt; Especially adjacent to ridgelines in all aspects: Over a wide area snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt;</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>The weather will be cold. The avalanche danger will persist.</tendencyComment>
